# Migration to Textile-Compatible Dataset (DTD)

The original project proposal for the "Generative Fashion Designer" focuses on creating traditional Pakistani textile patterns (e.g., Ajrak, Khaddar, Phulkari). Since a public, pre-curated dataset of these specific textiles does not exist (the proposal notes it must be collected manually), we need a compatible stand-in that models high-frequency patterns, textures, and fabrics in RGB color.

This plan outlines the migration from the grayscale `Fashion-MNIST` (images of shirts/shoes) to the **Describable Textures Dataset (DTD)**, which contains 5,640 images across 47 texture categories (including `paisley`, `woven`, `interlaced`, `knitted`, `zigzag`). This represents a massive leap in complexity and visual fidelity, aligning much closer with the proposal's goals.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Because DTD images are full-color textures rather than simple 28x28 grayscale icons, this upgrade significantly increases the computational requirements:
> 1. **RGB Color**: Models will generate 3-channel RGB images instead of 1-channel grayscale.
> 2. **Resolution**: We will increase the generation resolution from 32x32 to **64x64** (or 128x128 if your RTX 4050 6GB VRAM permits). 
> 3. **Classes**: Conditional models will train on 47 distinct texture classes instead of 10 clothing categories.
>
> Please confirm if you approve using DTD as the dataset, and if you are comfortable targeting 64x64 resolution for training on your RTX 4050.

